I am referring to this code in the XMLRPC API:

``` python
    def getNetTimeSinceLastUpdate(self):
        return getTimeSinceLastUpdate('net')

    def getDiskTimeSinceLastUpdate(self):
        return getTimeSinceLastUpdate('net')

    def getProcessDiskTimeSinceLastUpdate(self):
        return getTimeSinceLastUpdate('process_disk')
```

The times are already stored as part of the individual IO object data dictionaries (i.e. netstat, for networking).  The last update time data is available through the related api call. Java Glances API for example uses this time when it gets the network data to calculate traffic per second.

Moreover, since the function getTimeSinceLastUpdate also resets the timer, I think it might make the data incorrect in certain cases.

I ran a test case to prove it might make incorrect data:

```
Testing getNetworkTimeSinceLastUpdate();
Time since last network update: 4.7793 seconds // <--- the time is reset on the server here
Testing getNetwork():
Net[wlan0]: Rx/s: 196M Tx/s: 6.5M TOTAL: Rx/Tx 834M / 45M <--- My internet connection is 20Mbps download, not 196MBps!!
```
